    <h2>What affects BBQ grill repair cost in Los Angeles</h2>
    <div class="factors-grid">
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128027;</div><h3>Spiders &mdash; LA&rsquo;s #1 grill failure cause</h3><p>Yellow sac spiders and black widows nest in burner venturi tubes year-round in LA backyards. Blocked venturi tubes cause dangerous gas buildup and ignition failure. Spider clearing is always checked first &mdash; it&rsquo;s often the only thing needed.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128293;</div><h3>Year-round use accelerates wear</h3><p>LA grills are used 12 months a year, not seasonally. Igniters, burner ports, and regulators wear faster than manufacturer replacement schedules assume for seasonal use. We assess actual component condition, not just calendar age.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127774;</div><h3>Coastal salt air corrosion</h3><p>Properties within 5 miles of the ocean see accelerated stainless steel corrosion, burner perforation, and valve pitting. We assess outdoor grills for corrosion and advise on component replacement before failure creates a gas hazard.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127991;</div><h3>Brand and built-in vs. freestanding</h3><p>Weber, Napoleon, and Char-Broil have inexpensive OEM igniters and burners available quickly. Lynx, Hestan, and Kalamazoo use proprietary burner systems at premium pricing. Built-in grills in outdoor kitchens may require access work adding labor.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128204;</div><h3>Regulator lockout &mdash; often misdiagnosed</h3><p>A gas regulator can enter safety lockout mode if the tank valve is opened too quickly &mdash; restricting gas flow and making the grill appear to have low pressure. We test for lockout before recommending regulator replacement. Lockout resets free; regulator replacement costs money.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#9875;</div><h3>Post-repair gas leak test</h3><p>Every gas grill repair that involves gas components ends with a leak test. Standard on every call. We don&rsquo;t leave until the grill has been confirmed leak-free and all burners have been test-fired.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Repair vs. Replace</p>
    <h2>When to repair a gas grill, when to replace it</h2>
    <p class="lead">Built-in outdoor kitchen grills almost always favor repair. Freestanding grills depend on the failure and the unit value.</p>
    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card repair">
        <h3>Repair makes sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Built-in outdoor kitchen grill &mdash; replacement requires hardscape work</li>
          <li>Lynx, Hestan, or DCS &mdash; these last 15&ndash;20 years with maintenance</li>
          <li>Igniter, burner, or spider cleaning only</li>
          <li>Regulator lockout (free reset, no parts)</li>
          <li>Total repair under 40% of grill replacement value</li>
          <li>Single burner failure on a multi-burner grill</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card replace">
        <h3>Replace makes more sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Budget freestanding grill with severe firebox corrosion</li>
          <li>Multiple burner perforations from coastal corrosion</li>
          <li>Main valve failure on a 15+ year old non-luxury unit</li>
          <li>Firebox structurally compromised</li>
          <li>Parts discontinued with no reliable ETA</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

